INSERT INTO posts VALUES(9,'All about essays','all-about-essays',unistr('Building a blog sounds simple at first. You imagine a clean homepage, a few posts, maybe some pictures, and a place where your ideas feel organized. Then you actually start building it and realize it is not just “a page,” it is a whole system. You have routes, controllers, views, a database, and tiny details like slugs, validation, and image paths that can break everything if they are off by one character. But that challenge is also the point. A blog is one of the best projects to build because it forces you to learn the real basics of web development in a way that feels personal and worth finishing.\u000d\u000a\u000d\u000aThe first big lesson a blog teaches you is that content needs structure. When you write posts in your notes app, you can throw anything anywhere. On a blog site, your ideas need a home. A database table gives each post an identity: title, body, publish date, maybe a category, maybe a pinned flag. That structure is what makes your content searchable and organized. It is also what allows your blog to grow without turning into a mess. When you save a post as a row in a database, your site is no longer a bunch of static pages. It becomes a living archive.'),unistr('Building a blog sounds simple at first. You imagine a clean homepage, a few posts, maybe some pictures, and a place where your ideas feel organized. Then you actually start building it and realize it is not just “a page,” it is a whole system. You have routes, controllers, views, a database, and tiny details like slugs, validation, and image paths that can break everything if they are off by one character. But that challenge is also the point. A blog is one of the best projects to build because it forces you to learn the real basics of web development in a way that feels personal and worth finishing.\u000d\u000a\u000d\u000aThe first big lesson a blog teaches you is that content needs structure. When you write posts in 